Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**In `App.xaml.cs`**, override `CreateWindow` and use a custom Window subclass:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", NotesViewModel.Current.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**In your ViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    public static NotesViewModel Current { get; private set; } = null!;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public NotesViewModel()
    {
        Current = this;
        // Restore on initial launch too
        DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| Where to save | `OnStopped` (backgrounded) + `OnDestroying` (Android back button) |
| Where to restore | `OnResumed` + constructor for first launch |
| Keep it fast | `Preferences` is ideal for small text â€” avoid DB writes here |
| `Resumed` â‰  first launch | `Resumed` only fires after `Stopped`, not on initial startup |

`Preferences.Set/Get` uses `SharedPreferences` on Android and `NSUserDefaults` on iOS, so it's fast and survives process termination.
